84
00:06:26,240 --> 00:06:29,720
He is underage. I should be in charge of the money.

85
00:06:30,720 --> 00:06:34,320
Sorry for saying this, but I think you're a bit naive.

86
00:06:34,400 --> 00:06:35,400
What?

87
00:06:35,480 --> 00:06:39,480
What did you expect? It's his money, he won't give it to you.

88
00:06:39,840 --> 00:06:42,320
He is no longer a child. I don't think I can help you.

89
00:06:42,440 --> 00:06:45,240
You are a father. Would you give Bruno 200 euros a month?

90
00:06:45,320 --> 00:06:48,520
-Don't be crazy. -So why did you call me naive and crazy.

91
00:06:48,600 --> 00:06:50,140
You got yourself in this mess.

92
00:06:50,140 --> 00:06:52,040
You wanted to exploit your ex, right?

93
00:06:52,640 --> 00:06:56,240
You had what you wanted. But you didn't foresee this detail.

94
00:06:56,920 --> 00:06:58,880
Shall we go to the bar next door and talk calmly?

95
00:06:58,960 --> 00:07:01,560
I don't think so. I'm leaving. Don't tell Gerard I came.

96
00:07:36,400 --> 00:07:38,280
Pol Rubio, as always, the first one to finish.

97
00:07:56,160 --> 00:07:58,280
-Pol, how did it go? -What do you think?

98
00:07:58,920 --> 00:08:01,680
You handed it over too soon. I think Hitler will suspect.

99
00:08:02,040 --> 00:08:03,760
Let him suspect. I did study.

100
00:08:03,880 --> 00:08:09,240
I know that you studied. Listen, last night it was a joke.

101
00:08:09,400 --> 00:08:11,520
I don't know why you put it that way. We are friends.

102
00:08:13,240 --> 00:08:14,640
As long as you don't touch me.

103
00:08:21,960 --> 00:08:25,480
So, according to Aristotle, man is a social being.

104
00:08:25,560 --> 00:08:27,040
Which certainly will be on the test.

105
00:08:27,640 --> 00:08:28,920
-But... -It is too much!

106
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:31,720
Keep silent. According to Aristotle,

107
00:08:33,880 --> 00:08:37,000
without friends, you can't reach eudaimonia.

108
00:08:37,800 --> 00:08:40,520
In Greek, eudaimonia means happiness.

109
00:08:41,400 --> 00:08:45,160
To Aristotle, life's goal is the pursuit of happiness.

110
00:08:45,320 --> 00:08:47,520
Nowadays, we have turned it into an unhealthy obsession.

111
00:08:47,600 --> 00:08:50,400
We think it is a right we have, not an aspiration,

112
00:08:50,480 --> 00:08:51,880
and that leads to frustration.

113
00:08:52,400 --> 00:08:56,040
Some say happiness is in little things.

114
00:08:56,120 --> 00:08:58,920
The new fad is to talk about the coffee's smell,

115
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:01,600
about the singing birds... Bullshit. That's not happiness.

116
00:09:05,720 --> 00:09:07,640
Who in here is happy?

117
00:09:13,080 --> 00:09:14,080
Gerard.

118
00:09:14,520 --> 00:09:17,360
Well, I am. In general, everything is going well for me.

119
00:09:17,440 --> 00:09:19,200
-Good. -But not always.

120
00:09:19,720 --> 00:09:22,400
-In general? -Yes, in general.

121
00:09:23,600 --> 00:09:28,520
To Aristotle, happiness is not a state. It's an activity.

122
00:09:29,120 --> 00:09:31,240
It's only at the end of life

123
00:09:31,960 --> 00:09:33,880
you can say whether you are happy or not.

124
00:09:35,080 --> 00:09:38,600
Do you want to be happy? Aristotle says you have to work for it.

125
00:09:41,840 --> 00:09:44,760
-What? -That we have to work for happiness?

126
00:09:45,240 --> 00:09:47,560
Work is fucking slavery.

127
00:09:47,640 --> 00:09:49,060
Just look at people getting

128
00:09:49,070 --> 00:09:51,400
on the subway everyday, they look miserable.

129
00:09:51,480 --> 00:09:54,200
I don't know. Can you be happy working?

130
00:09:54,600 --> 00:09:56,240
You got half a point in the exam.

131
00:09:57,200 --> 00:09:59,240
Let's go, bull!

132
00:09:59,960 --> 00:10:03,080
That's what I want you to do. Thinking. Questioning.

133
00:10:05,080 --> 00:10:08,000
For the next class, you have to write on a piece of paper

134
00:10:08,080 --> 00:10:10,280
what do you think of happiness.

135
00:10:10,880 --> 00:10:12,100
-Does it have to be long?

136
00:10:12,100 --> 00:10:14,120
-It could be one sentence. And anonymous.

137
00:10:14,760 --> 00:10:17,440
Gerard, take this. Because everything is going well for you,

138
00:10:17,520 --> 00:10:18,880
you're in charge of collecting the papers.

139
00:10:23,200 --> 00:10:26,000
-Can you change it on Thursday? -Again, Gloria?

140
00:10:26,080 --> 00:10:26,910
It would help me a lot.

141
00:10:26,910 --> 00:10:28,520
I'm in charge of something else on Thursday.

142
00:10:28,600 --> 00:10:31,640
But we had agreed that on Thursday. Another thing, Gloria.

143
00:10:32,080 --> 00:10:34,120
-Yes. -How many copies did you make?

144
00:10:34,320 --> 00:10:35,560
-For your exam? -Yes.

145
00:10:35,680 --> 00:10:39,040
-Twenty five. -Are you sure? Because I counted only 24.

146
00:10:39,440 --> 00:10:41,560
How strange. I'm sure I made 25.

147
00:10:41,640 --> 00:10:43,280
-Are you sure? -Eugeni!

148
00:10:44,400 --> 00:10:48,280
And when you left the copies at the staffroom, was anyone there?

149
00:10:52,800 --> 00:10:54,320
Eugeni, it's impossible.

150
00:10:54,400 --> 00:10:57,920
If someone stole the test, you'll know when you see the grades.

151
00:10:58,160 --> 00:10:59,240
-Slow down. -Thank you, Gloria.

152
00:10:59,320 --> 00:11:00,800
You can't be sure about it.

153
00:11:14,720 --> 00:11:16,640
-Hello. -Hello, Joan. Come in.

154
00:11:19,160 --> 00:11:20,600
What's up? Tell me.

155
00:11:20,680 --> 00:11:22,280
At the end, you didn't explain

156
00:11:22,280 --> 00:11:24,640
the topic of justice according to Aristotle.

157
00:11:24,720 --> 00:11:26,560
-And because it will be on the exam...

158
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:28,360
-Yes, I'll explain in class tomorrow.

159
00:11:29,120 --> 00:11:31,960
Okay. Then, that's all.

160
00:11:32,240 --> 00:11:34,320
Since you're here, sit down.

161
00:11:39,480 --> 00:11:40,680
Look.

162
00:11:43,760 --> 00:11:46,680
Justice is a medium term between two ends.

163
00:11:48,080 --> 00:11:49,960
Each end is the injustice.

164
00:11:51,280 --> 00:11:54,480
It is unfair that you commit injustice on someone...

165
00:11:54,760 --> 00:11:58,080
or that you allow someone to commit injustice on you.

166
00:11:59,200 --> 00:12:03,080
-Okay. -In the middle, is the justice.

167
00:12:04,640 --> 00:12:09,200
-And without justice, there's no euda... -Eudaimonia.

168
00:12:12,320 --> 00:12:14,720
-Have you ever been unfair to someone? -No.

169
00:12:15,720 --> 00:12:17,520
Was someone unfair to you?

170
00:12:20,880 --> 00:12:23,840
-I'll come back later. -No, I'm leaving.

171
00:12:25,240 --> 00:12:26,560
We'll talk later, right?

172
00:12:33,920 --> 00:12:35,160
Man, it's a classic.

173
00:12:35,240 --> 00:12:37,080
I'm not used to reading these things.

174
00:12:37,080 --> 00:12:39,120
Do you know if there is a movie about it?

175
00:12:40,440 --> 00:12:41,840
Your mother came.

176
00:12:42,880 --> 00:12:43,880
Fuck.

177
00:12:43,960 --> 00:12:46,880
She is very worried about the money you get each month.

178
00:12:46,960 --> 00:12:48,280
She asked me to talk with you.

179
00:12:48,360 --> 00:12:49,900
